

    Literal expressions:
        String literals (e.g., "hello", 'hello')
        Numeric literals (e.g., 42, 3.14)
        Boolean literals (e.g., true, false)
        Null literal (e.g., null)
        Undefined literal (e.g., undefined)

    Identifier expressions:
        Variable names (e.g., x, foo)
        Property access (e.g., obj.prop)

    Binary expressions:
        Arithmetic operators (e.g., 2 + 3, 5 * 2)
        Comparison operators (e.g., 2 == 3, 5 > 2)
        Logical operators (e.g., true && false, true || false)
        Assignment operators (e.g., x = 5, x += 2)

    Unary expressions:
        Prefix increment/decrement (e.g., ++x, --x)
        Postfix increment/decrement (e.g., x++, x--)
        Unary plus/minus (e.g., +x, -x)
        Logical not (e.g., !true)

    Function expressions:
        Function calls (e.g., foo(), bar(2, 3))
        Function definitions (e.g., function foo() {}, () => {})

    Object expressions:
        Object literals (e.g., { foo: 'bar', baz: 42 })
        Object property access (e.g., obj.foo)

    Array expressions:
        Array literals (e.g., [1, 2, 3], [])
        Array indexing (e.g., arr[0])

    Conditional expressions:
        Ternary operator (e.g., x ? y : z)
        
    Parenthesized expressions:
        Grouping expressions (e.g., (2 + 3) * 4)

This list should give you a good starting point for building your grammar. Keep in mind that JavaScript has many edge cases and nuances, so be prepared to handle those as well.
